		Comment <a href="#c_1713615001">2</a> by David
		posted on 10/7/2003 at 3:36 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I’m sorry to hear about your unfortunate experience with Dell. I have a story in which my computer began shutting off in much the same way you describe. Though never did pin down the cause, I too thought it could be related to CPU workload. But I had some shutoffs occur when I was certain the CPU was near idle.</p><p>I purchased a Dell Latitude C800 in June of 2001 and it worked perfectly (Once the LCD had to be replaced and another time the keyboard needed to be replaced, this was handled onsite by one of their friendly techs) until February of 2003 when one of the USB ports stopped working. A Dell technician came and replaced the entire motherboard because the USB ports were completely integrated. This was when the big problems started happening. With the new (refurbished actually) motherboard in, my Latitude C800 would shut off at least once every two hours. I’m talking about a cold, hard shut off. In spite of the random shut offs I was able to work (ctrl-S every 20 seconds) without losing data. After a call to Dell another tech came and replaced the motherboard again. This one had almost the same problem only now it was shutting off at least once every two days. Not as bad but still very disconcerting. Here’s where it gets interesting.</p><p>I called Dell and I must have spent 4 hours on the phone being very polite but relentless in my pursuit of satisfaction. I convinced Dell that I had good reason for not trusting their refurbished motherboards at this point. All I had to do was to wait for a call back from a “manager”. The manager called later that afternoon and informed my I would be receiving a brand new (not refurbished) Dell Latitude C840! The machine arrived and I transferred my data and settled in on the new machine. When comfortable that all was good I securely wiped all data the old laptop and sent it back to Dell.</p><p>I’m still using the Latitude C840 without a single trouble (knock on wood) and I’m very happy with Dell. I think overall I would have been most content to have never had the problem in the first place.</p><p>There are a couple things I’ve taken away from this experience:</p><p>1) Always, always, always be polite with the people on the other end of the phone. This doesn’t mean you have to roll over, be persistent and never give up but always be polite. This is hard for me because my blood has a very low boiling point with the “idiot monkeys” swinging from the corporate phone trees.</p><p>2) Always buy the expensive, next business day service, support plan upfront. Especially when buying a laptop. In my case the plan had already paid for itself with the replacement of the LCD and the keyboard. Add to that the 2 replaced motherboards and the entirely replaced laptop and the extended super service plan was well worth $300.</p></div>
