		Comment <a href="#c_1713615000">3</a> by Nolan
		posted on 10/7/2003 at 8:36 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Having worked as a Technical Support Representative at a software company (that probably wishes to remain nameless) in the past, I can tell you that, for some reason people LOVE to lie about their computer abilities, what they've "already tried", and what they "swear they didn't do to the machine."</p><p>Kids would call trying to get brand new games to work on 5 year old machines, lacking the required hardware, downloading hacks off the net, and various other things that aren't (of course) supported. We would commonly make "crack smoking" files - lists of the strangest phone calls we had the "pleasure" of dealing with that day.</p><p>"Why can't I get your Windows 98 game to work on my Mac? Or on my old DOS computer?"</p><p>"I only have a 3.5" drive. This game is on 5.25 discs. If I cut the edges off so it's 3.5 in size, will it work in my drive?"</p><p>"I think your game reformatted my hard drive. I'm suing!"</p><p>and my personal favorite...</p><p>"I need a new instruction manual, because my pig at the last one."  (true story)</p><p>...and the like were all common phone calls for my group.</p><p>For whatever it's worth, the tech rep taking your call probably heard "I'm a software engineer, I know what I'm doing" 10 times that day, and 9 of the 10 didn't know what Ctrl-Alt-Delete does.  So when he/she gets to you, they're probably thinking "oh...ANOTHER supposed engineer" and walk you through the steps as they do everyone else, so they KNOW it was done that way, and can try to solve the problem with more of a known quantity.</p><p>I feel the same way you do about these calls, and I wish things worked differently (I had a similar problem calling Direct TV last week).  But having been in their shoes, I think I understand why they do it...even if I still don't agree. :)</p></div>
